Forecasting

Stephen Turner

November 16, 2017

Forecasting flu outbreaks

library(tidyverse)
library(prophet)
library(cdcfluview)
library(lubridate)
theme_set(theme_bw())

Get data

Let’s get the data from the CDC’s Influenza-like illness API.

flu <- ilinet(region = "national") %>% 
  select(week_start, starts_with("age"), ilitotal, total_patients) %>%
  filter(year(week_start)>=2003)
flu

Forecast future outbreaks

The last week we have data on is 2017-10-30. Let’s forecast outbreaks for the next five years.

# Run the model
m <- prophet(flu %>% select(ds=week_start, y=ilitotal))
# Make a future data frame
future <- make_future_dataframe(m, periods=365*5)
# Predict the future
forecast <- predict(m, future)
tail(forecast[c('ds', 'yhat', 'yhat_lower', 'yhat_upper')])

Plot the future

Flu outbreaks forecasted for the next 5 years.

Trend, uncertainty, and yearly seasonality.

Forecast Peyton Manning Wikipedia Page Views

Let’s look at a time series of daily page views for the Wikipedia page for Peyton Manning scraped using the Wikipediatrend package. This example illustrates forecasting that accounts for multiple seasonality, changing growth rates, and the ability to model special days (such as Manning’s playoff and superbowl appearances). The data is available here.

Process data and forecast

Import and log transform the data to deal with extreme outliers, then predict the future.

manning <- read_csv("data/peyton_manning_prophet.csv") %>% mutate(y=log(y))
m <- prophet(manning)
future <- make_future_dataframe(m, periods = 365*2)
forecast <- predict(m, future)
tail(forecast[c('ds', 'yhat', 'yhat_lower', 'yhat_upper')])

Plot future page views

Predicted page views for Wikipedia entry on Peyton Manning.

Trend/uncertainty, and weekly + yearly seasonality.
